  "prompt": "College and NCAA Football: (NFL) In overtime, is the kicking team allowed to do an onside kick and if successful does the other team get the ball afterwards?",
  "response": "In both the NFL and NCAA (college) football, overtime rules differ significantly, especially concerning kickoffs and the use of onside kicks. Here's a breakdown of how each league handles these situations:\n\n---\n\n**NFL Overtime Rules:**\n\n1. **Overtime Format:**\n   - The overtime period is a single 10-minute possession (as of the 2023 season).\n   - A kickoff is used to start overtime, similar to the start of a regular game.\n\n2. **Possession and Scoring:**\n   - **First Possession:**\n     - If the receiving team scores a **touchdown** or a **safety** on their initial possession, the game ends immediately, and they win.\n     - If they score a **field goal**, the opposing team gets an opportunity to possess the ball.\n   - **Subsequent Possessions:**\n     - If both teams score field goals, the game continues with alternating possessions until a winner is determined.\n     - If neither team scores, the game can end in a tie during the regular season (though playoff overtime continues until a winner is decided).\n\n3. **Onside Kicks in Overtime:**\n   - **Allowed:** The kicking team can attempt an onside kick during the kickoff in overtime, just as they might during regular play.\n   - **Successful Onside Kick:**\n     - If the kicking team successfully recovers the onside kick, they gain possession of the ball.\n     - The game then continues with the kicking team in possession, allowing them the opportunity to score and win the game.\n   - **Outcome if Onside Kick Fails:**\n     - If the onside kick is unsuccessful and the receiving team gains possession, the receiving team proceeds with their possession as outlined in the overtime rules.\n\n---\n\n**NCAA (College) Football Overtime Rules:**\n\n1. **Overtime Format:**\n   - Each overtime period consists of each team getting a possession from the opponent's **25-yard line**.\n   - There is no game clock, but the play clock and standard game rules apply.\n\n2. **Possession and Scoring:**\n   - Both teams have an equal opportunity to possess the ball and score.\n   - After the first overtime, teams must attempt a two-point conversion after a touchdown.\n   - Starting with the fifth overtime, teams alternate two-point conversion attempts instead of full possessions.\n\n3. **Onside Kicks in Overtime:**\n   - **Not Applicable:** The NCAA overtime format does not involve kickoffs, punts, or any standard kicking plays that would allow for onside kicks.\n   - **Possession Method:** Each team begins their possession by running a play from the 25-yard line, making onside kicks irrelevant in this context.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:**\n\n- **NFL:** During overtime kickoffs, the kicking team *can* attempt an onside kick. If successful, they gain possession and have the opportunity to score and win the game without the opposing team automatically receiving the ball afterward.\n  \n- **NCAA (College):** The overtime format is structured around alternating offensive possessions from a specific yard line, eliminating the possibility of onside kicks. There are no kicking plays in overtime, so the concept of an onside kick does not apply.\n\nUnderstanding these differences is crucial, especially for fans and participants who follow or play in both leagues, as strategies and possibilities vary based on the specific rules governing overtime in each.",
